<p><b>Nassim Nicholas Taleb</b> (born 1960) (<a href="/wiki/Arabic_language" title="Arabic language">Arabic</a>: <span lang="ar" xml:lang="ar">نسيم نيقولا نجيب طالب</span>‎) (alternative spellings of first name: <b>Nessim</b> or <b>Nissim</b>) is a literary <a href="/wiki/Essayist" title="Essayist" class="mw-redirect">essayist</a>, <a href="/wiki/Epistemology" title="Epistemology">epistemologist</a>, <a href="/wiki/Polymath" title="Polymath">polymath</a>, researcher, and former practitioner of <a href="/wiki/Mathematical_finance" title="Mathematical finance">mathematical finance</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2" title=""><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3" title=""><span>[</span>4<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4" title=""><span>[</span>5<span>]</span></a></sup> A specialist in financial <a href="/wiki/Derivative_(finance)" title="Derivative (finance)">derivatives</a><a href="http://fct.u-paris10.fr/FCT-APP/visualiserpub.do?code_these=9616484A" class="external autonumber" title="http://fct.u-paris10.fr/FCT-APP/visualiserpub.do?code_these=9616484A" rel="nofollow">[3]</a> (while critical of the industry), he held a "day job" in a lengthy senior trading and <a href="/wiki/Financial_mathematics" title="Financial mathematics" class="mw-redirect">financial mathematics</a> career in a number of <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York City</a>'s <a href="/wiki/Wall_Street" title="Wall Street">Wall Street</a> firms, before starting a second career as a scholar in the <a href="/wiki/Epistemology" title="Epistemology">epistemology</a> of <a href="/wiki/Chance" title="Chance">chance</a> events to focus on his project of mapping how to live and act in a world we do not understand, and how to come to grips with randomness and the unknown&#160;—which includes his <a href="/wiki/Black_swan_theory" title="Black swan theory">black swan theory</a> of unexpected rare events.<sup id="cite_ref-Edge_5-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Edge-5" title=""><span>[</span>6<span>]</span></a></sup>. Taleb has also, in the wake of the economic crisis that started in 2008, become an activist for a "Black Swan robust society"<sup id="cite_ref-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-6" title=""><span>[</span>7<span>]</span></a></sup>,<sup id="cite_ref-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-7" title=""><span>[</span>8<span>]</span></a></sup>.</p>
<p>Taleb's extremely idiosyncratic literary approach consists of providing a modern-day brand of philosophical tale by mixing narrative fiction, often semi-autobiographical, with <a href="/wiki/Erudition" title="Erudition">erudition</a> and scientific commentary.</p>
